'''Alimuddin''' ([[Urdu]]: '''<U+0639><U+0644><U+06CC><U+0645> <U+0627><U+0644><U+062F><U+06CC><U+0646>'''&lrm;; 15 December 1930 &ndash; 12 July 2012) was a [[Pakistan]]i [[cricket]]er who played 25 [[Test cricket|Tests]] for [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] between 1954 and 1962. A fast-scoring, right-handed [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opening batsman]] and occasional [[Leg break|right-arm leg break]] [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]], he was the youngest player ever to appear in [[first-class cricket]], aged 12 years and 73 days. In international cricket, he scored 1,091 [[Run (cricket)|runs]] at the [[Batting average#Cricket|average]] of 25.37, including two [[Century (cricket)|centuries]] and seven fifties. In 1954, he was a member of the Pakistani squad which toured [[England national cricket team|England]] and recorded Pakistan's first Test match win. Former [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]]i [[Captain (cricket)|captain]] [[Mushtaq Mohammad]] said about him that he was "a thorough gentleman as well as a great cricketer for Pakistan".<ref name="mushtaq">{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/top-stories/Mushtaq-Mohammad-salutes-Alimuddin-as-ex-opener-dies-at-81/articleshow/14858078.cms | title=Mushtaq Mohammad salutes Alimuddin as ex-opener dies at 81 |work=[[Times of India]] | date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>

== First-class career ==
During his career Alimuddin played 140 first-class matches and scored 7,275 [[Run (cricket)|runs]], with the [[Batting average#Cricket|average]] of 32.77, including 14 centuries and 38 fifties; he also took 40 wickets.<ref name="Profile"/> Critics considered him to be an excellent fielder.<ref name="daily times"/> He made his debut for [[Rajasthan cricket team|Rajasthan]] aged only 12 years 73 days, becoming the youngest player to have played [[first-class cricket]].<ref name="SMH">{{cite web | url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/obituaries/early-firstclass-start-just-one-claim-to-cricket-fame-20120812-242jx.html | title=Early first-class start just one claim to cricket fame | first=Gerry | last=Carman | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] (SMH) | date=13 August 2012 | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In 1942<U+2013>43, he played his maiden match in the [[Ranji Trophy]], scoring 13 and 27 runs in his two innings.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/17/17378.html | title=Baroda v Rajputana&nbsp;<U+2013> Ranji Trophy 1942<U+2013>43 |publisher=[[CricketArchive]] | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> His highest score in first-class cricket was 142, against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in 1954.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/576715.html | title=Pakistan tour of England&nbsp;<U+2013> Worcestershire v Pakistanis |publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Domestically, Alimuddin represented [[Sindh cricket team|Sindh]], Rajasthan, [[Karachi cricket team|Karachi]], [[Bahawalpur cricket team|Bahawalpur]] and [[Gujarat cricket team|Gujarat]],<ref name="Profile">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/38992.html |title=Player Profile: Alimuddin | publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/986/all_teams.html | title=Teams Alimuddin played for |publisher=CricketArchive | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> and became the first Pakistani batsman to face a ball bowled by an international bowler on Pakistani soil, in a match between the [[Sindh cricket team|Sindh]] and [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indians]] in 1948.<ref name="daily times">{{cite web| url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C07%5C13%5Cstory_13-7-2012_pg2_6 | title=Pakistan's to former Test to opener Alimuddin passes away in London |publisher=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] |author=Staff report |date=13 July 2012 | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/572161.html | title=West Indies vs Pakistan&nbsp;<U+2013> FC match|publisher=ESPNcricinfo | date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/407679/cricket-pakistans-legendary-batsman-alimuddin-dies-at-81/ | title=Cricket: Former Pakistani Opener Alimuddin died at 81 |work=[[Express Tribune]] | date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> During Pakistan's 1954 tour of England, Alimuddin scored more than 700 runs, including two centuries in the first two matches.<ref name="E1954">{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/155167.html | title=WISDEN <U+2013> Pakistan in England, 1954 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Leslie |last=Smith |date= |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> He was most successful during 1961<U+2013>62, scoring 1,020 runs in 12 matches at an average of 51.00.<ref name=Fcbatting>{{cite web| url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/986/f_Batting_by_Season.html | title=First-class Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Alimuddin |publisher=CricketArchive | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In the same season he captained Karachi, leading the team to victories in the [[Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]] and Ayub Zonal Trophy.<ref name="SMH"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://static.espncricinfo.com//db//NATIONAL//PAK//HISTORY//quaid.html | title=Quaid-E-Azam Trophy&nbsp;<U+2013> A brief history&nbsp;<U+2013> Winners |publisher=CricketArchive | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pcb.com.pk/quaideazam-trophy-196162/match/461.html | title=Quaid-e-Azam Trophy 1961/62 |publisher=[[Pakistan Cricket Board]] | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/25/25353.html | title=Karachi v North Zone |publisher=CricketArchive | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> His final season in first-class cricket was 1967<U+2013>68.<ref name=Fcbatting/>

== International career ==
[[File:Nat Std01.JPG|thumb|alt=A view of a cricket ground during a match|Alimuddin made both of his centuries at the [[National Stadium, Karachi|National Stadium]], [[Karachi]].<ref name="1st100"/><ref name="2nd100"/>]]
Alimuddin played 25 Test matches for [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] during his career and scored 1,091 runs in international cricket at the average of 25.37. He made two [[Century (cricket)|centuries]] and seven fifties.<ref name="Profile"/> Cricket critics believed that he possessed a sound technique.<ref name="youngest">{{cite news| url=http://dawn.com/2012/07/12/legendary-batsman-alimuddin-passes-away-in-london/ | title=Legendary opener Alimuddin passed away in London |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|The Dawn]] | date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In Test matches, Alimuddin established an effective opening partnership with [[Hanif Mohammad]].<ref name="SMH"/>

Alimuddin started his international career against [[England national cricket team|England]] in June 1954, at the [[Lord's Cricket Ground]], in a match in which he scored 19 runs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/62773.html | title=England vs Pakistan <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 1st Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In the fourth Test of the same series Pakistan beat England by 24 runs, recording their first Test win over them to become the first team to defeat England during their maiden tour.<ref name="E1954"/> Alimuddin managed to score 10 runs in the match.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/62776.html | title=England vs Pakistan <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 4th Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In 1954<U+2013>55, he played, against [[India national cricket team|India]], in Pakistan's first home Tests, finishing the series as the leading run scorer with 332; he made three fifties and in the fifth match scored 103 [[not out]] at the [[National Stadium, Karachi]], his first international century.<ref name="1st100">{{cite web| url=http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/21/21447.html | title= Pakistan v India in 1954/55 (5th Test) |publisher=CricketArchive | accessdate=21 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/current/series/62326.html | title=India tour of Pakistan 1954<U+2013>55 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=105;type=seriesl | title=Cricket Records <U+2013> Records <U+2013> India in Pakistan Test Series, 1954/55 <U+2013> Most runs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> He was the first batsman ever to make an international century on the Ground.<ref name="Alimuddin_died">{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/572137.html | title=Former Pakistani cricketer Alimuddin died|first=Umar |last= Farooq | date = 12 July 2012|publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>

Alimuddin also toured [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] as a part of Pakistan cricket team in 1957<U+2013>58. He was not successful in the series and his highest score remained 41 runs which he made in the fourth Test at the [[Bourda]], [[Georgetown, Guyana]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/986/t_Batting_by_Season.html | title=Batting test and Fielding in Each Season by Alimuddin |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/62838.html | title=West Indies vs Pakistan <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 4th Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In 1962, under the captaincy of [[Javed Burki]], Pakistan visited England where they played a five Test mach series.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/61451.html?template=fixtures | title=Pakistan tour of England, 1962 <U+2013> Fixtures |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In the fifth Test at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]], a low scoring match for Pakistan, Alimuddin's scores of 50 and 60 made him the team's highest scorer of the match.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/62918.html | title=England  vs Pakistan <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 5th Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> In the fifth Test of the home series against England in 1962, he scored his career best 109 runs at the National Stadium.<ref name="2nd100">{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/62900.html | title= Pakistan vs England  <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 5th Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> He played his last match against England in [[Trent Bridge]], [[Nottingham]] in 1962.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/62919.html | title=England vs Pakistan <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 4th Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>

Former West Indian [[all-rounder]] [[Collie Smith]] was his only wicket in international cricket.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/62835.html | title=West Indies vs Pakistan <U+2013> Test Series <U+2013> 1st Test |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Alimuddin was born [[Ajmer]], a city in [[British India]] (now [[India]]), on 15 December 1930.<ref name="Profile"/> After the [[partition of India]], he shifted to [[Karachi]] along with his family. He lived in London and never married, instead providing for his family. [[Pakistan International Airlines]] (PIA) had given him an opportunity to work at [[London Heathrow Airport]].<ref name="Alimuddin_died"/> His brothers, Salimuddin played nine first class cricket from English and Pakistani teams during 1954<U+2013>1963, while Azimuddin appeared in a match from [[Rajputana]] during 1942<U+2013>43.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/42960.html | title=Player profile:Salimuddin |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/26768.html | title=Player profile:Azimuddin |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref> His nephew James Uddin, the son of Salimuddin, is also a cricketer and currently plays domestic cricket in England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/512710.html | title=Player profile:James Uddin |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref>

== Death ==
On 12 July 2012, Alimuddin died in [[Northwick Park Hospital]], [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]], [[London]].<ref name="mushtaq"/><ref name="Alimuddin_died"/> He suffered from [[Cardiovascular disease|heart]] and [[Respiratory disease|lung]] diseases. He also had [[Renal failure|kidney failure]] and was on [[dialysis]].<ref name="Alimuddin_died"/> The [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] (PCB) released a press statement expressing sorrow and conveying condolences to Alimuddin's family.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pcb.com.pk/press-release/pcb-condoles-the-death-of-pakistan-s-former-test-cricketer-alimuddin.html |title=PCB condoles the death of Pakistan's to former Test Cricketer Alimuddin |publisher=Pakistan Cricket Board |date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/lahore/13-Jul-2012/zaka-condoles-alimuddin-s-death |title=Zaka condoles Alimuddin's death  |work=[[The Nation (Pakistani newspaper)|The Nation]] |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>

